04765nam a22006855i 9780674043244DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222006mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740432447 a10.4159/97806740432442doi  a(DE-B1597)574542  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHM1096 ǂb S34 2003eb 7aLAW0130002bisacsh04a303.3/851 aSchauer, Frederick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProfiles, Probabilities, and Stereotypes /cFrederick Schauer. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Painting with a Broad Brush -- t1. In Training with the Greeks -- t2. Pit Bulls, Golden Retrievers, and Other Dangerous Dogs -- t3. A Ride on the Blue Bus -- t4. Eighty-Year-Old Pilots and Twelve-Year-Old Voters -- t5. The Women of the Virginia Military Institute -- t6. The Profilers -- t7. The Usual Suspects -- t8. Two Cheers for Procrustes -- t9. Ships with Altered Names -- t10. The Generality of Law -- t11. Generality, Community, and the Wars of the Roqueforts -- tCoda: From the Justice of Generality to the Generality of Justice -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book employs a careful, rigorous, yet lively approach to the timely question of whether we can justly generalize about members of a group on the basis of statistical tendencies of that group. For instance, should a military academy exclude women because, on average, women are more sensitive to hazing than men? Should airlines force all pilots to retire at age sixty, even though most pilots at that age have excellent vision? Can all pit bulls be banned because of the aggressive characteristics of the breed? And, most controversially, should government and law enforcement use racial and ethnic profiling as a tool to fight crime and terrorism? Frederick Schauer strives to analyze and resolve these prickly questions. When the law "thinks like an actuary"--makes decisions about groups based on averages--the public benefit can be enormous. On the other hand, profiling and stereotyping may lead to injustice. And many stereotypes are self-fulfilling, while others are simply spurious. How, then, can we decide which stereotypes are accurate, which are distortions, which can be applied fairly, and which will result in unfair stigmatization? These decisions must rely not only on statistical and empirical accuracy, but also on morality. Even statistically sound generalizations may sometimes have to yield to the demands of justice. But broad judgments are not always or even usually immoral, and we should not always dismiss them because of an instinctive aversion to stereotypes. As Schauer argues, there is good profiling and bad profiling. If we can effectively determine which is which, we stand to gain, not lose, a measure of justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674043244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674043244/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-de